![alt text](Screenshot 2026-03-01 230943.jpg)

This project demonstrates how to design and deploy a scalable and secure web architecture on Google Cloud Platform (GCP) using Managed Instance Groups (MIG), Autoscaling policies, IAM role management, and firewall configurations.
The architecture ensures that the application can automatically handle traffic spikes while maintaining strong security controls. 
A Managed Instance Group creates identical virtual machines from an Instance Template, and an Autoscaler dynamically adjusts the number of instances based on CPU utilization (target 50–60%). 
When workload increases, new VM instances are added automatically (scale-out), and when demand decreases, unnecessary instances are removed (scale-in) to optimize cost.
Security is implemented using a layered approach. Firewall rules allow only required web traffic (TCP 80/443) and restrict SSH access using Identity-Aware Proxy (IAP) or limited IP ranges. 
Identity and Access Management (IAM) enforces least-privilege access for administrators, ensuring that users can only perform actions permitted by their assigned roles. 
Virtual machines use dedicated service accounts to securely access other GCP services without hardcoding credentials.

This repository includes:

1. Step-by-step implementation guide
2. Architecture diagrams
3. Autoscaling configuration details
4. IAM role setup
5. Firewall rule configuration

The final design provides high availability, automatic scalability, cost efficiency, and strong infrastructure security within a Google Cloud environment.
